--- !u!114 &5241205162859610977
MonoBehaviour:
  m_ObjectHideFlags: 0
  m_CorrespondingSourceObject: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabInstance: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabAsset: {fileID: 0}
  m_GameObject: {fileID: 5154611913828351803}
  m_Enabled: 1
  m_EditorHideFlags: 0
  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: 29b480dc3b7c34901916c4e135caebb1, type: 3}
  m_Name: 
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: Assembly-CSharp::ArtifactController
  artifactData:
    description: 'The artifact  is a Yoruba Beaded Crown, or Ade, which serves as
      the most sacred symbol of royal authority among the Yoruba people of Nigeria.
      These crowns are not mere ornaments; they are viewed as spiritual vessels that
      empower the Oba (king) to rule with the wisdom of his ancestors.


      Historical
      and Spiritual Significance

      The tradition of the beaded crown is central
      to Yoruba political and religious life:


      Divine Origin: According to
      Yoruba cosmology, the right to wear a beaded crown was granted to the sons
      of Oduduwa, the legendary first king of Ile-Ife and progenitor of the Yoruba
      race.


      The Crown as a Deity: The crown itself is often treated as a
      sacred object that holds more power than the man wearing it. It is consecrated
      with secret medicinal materials placed inside the peak to protect and empower
      the Oba''s head.


      The Veil: The beads hanging from the rim form a veil
      that hides the king''s face. This serves to diminish his individual personality
      and focus the public''s attention on the divine office of kingship, while also
      protecting the people from the king''s powerful spiritual gaze.


      Key
      Symbolic Features

      The intricate beadwork on the crown carries specific
      meanings:


      The Bird (Okin): The prominent bird at the top (and sometimes
      others around the sides) represents the "Great Mothers" or female ancestors.
      It signifies that the Oba''s power is balanced by the spiritual watchfulness
      and support of women.


      The Faces: The stylized faces depicted in beads
      represent ancestors, specifically Oduduwa, signaling that the king is constantly
      under the guidance and scrutiny of past rulers.


      Vibrant Beadwork: The
      use of tiny, colorful glass beads was traditionally a sign of immense wealth
      and prestige, as these beads were often imported through long-standing trade
      networks.'
